<p>True and false are common concepts in all forms of computing. They’re critical to Boolean logic after all, but did you know that <strong>true</strong> and <strong>false</strong> are also commands on Linux? Do you know how to use them?</p><p>The simplest explanation is that the <strong>true</strong> command generates an exit code of 0 and that the <strong>false</strong> command generates an exit code of 1. This explanation, however, doesn’t provide much detail on how these commands can best be used.</p><p>In this post, we’ll look at how the <strong>true</strong> and <strong>false</strong> commands work and how you might put them to use on the command line or in your scripts.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/3646389/the-truth-about-linux-true-and-false-commands.html#jump">To read this article in full, please click here</a></p></section></article>